    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{t-9}{t^{2}+8}} = 0 }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{9\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>If a fraction<rsq/>s value is <m>0</m>, like <m>\frac{x}{y}=0</m>, then we can tell the numerator<rsq/>s value must be <m>0</m>, or <m>x=0</m> in this example.</p>
<p>The solution is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{t-9}{t^{2}+8}} \amp = 0 \\
   t - 9 \amp =0 \\
   t \amp = 9
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the denominator <m>t^2+8</m>, since <m>t^2 \ge 0</m>, we have <m>t^2+8 \gt 0</m>. In other words, the denominator<rsq/>s value cannot be <m>0</m>, so there is no domain constraints for this equation. The solution is <m>t = 9</m>.</p>
</solution>
